# Leadership & Management Class Program (1 hour / week)

## Phase 1 — Intro and Individual Leadership

### 1) Manager Tools: Three Pillars of Leadership (Safety, Growth/Challenge, Fulfillment)

- Brief review: (Kickoff) Course goals, norms, and how we’ll practice between sessions.
- Core content:
  - Surface real reasons people stay at (or leave) their jobs and cluster them into human needs.
  - Quick review of Maslow’s Hierarchy of Needs as a bridge to leadership.
  - Define the “job” of a manager: results through others, sustained over time.
  - Introduce the Three Pillars of Leadership (Safety, Growth/Challenge, Fulfillment) with concrete examples.
  - Connect participants’ reasons for staying to the Three Pillars model.
- In-session practice:
  - Individual reflection and discussion on the Three Pillars in their current role, plus one concrete behavior change they will experiment with before the next session.

### 2) Manager Tools: Power Triangle & The Trinity

- Brief review: Revisit the Three Pillars and early experiments from Lesson 1.
- Core content:
  - What managers can and can’t control; reframing helplessness into focused responsibility.
  - Power sources:
    - Position power: formal authority; when it works and when it backfires.
    - Relationship power: trust, credibility, history of care and competence.
    - Inspirational power: vision, meaning, modeling, and values-based influence.
  - Tradeoffs and balance among the three types of power; where senior and servant leaders aim to spend their time in the triangle.
  - Introduce the Manager Tools Trinity (1on1s, Feedback, Coaching, Delegation) as practical habits to provide the pillars and grow relationship/inspirational power.
- In-session practice:
  - Use the “burger” and work scenarios to compare using each type of power, then design one small 1on1 experiment to shift from position power toward relationship/inspirational power before the next session.

### 3) Manager Tools: The Trinity & Effective 1on1s

- Brief review: Power Triangle reflections; where you over/under-use position power.
- Core content:
  - Contrast “good” vs “bad” 1on1 experiences from the direct’s point of view.
  - Clarify why we do 1on1s, where they sit in the Trinity and Power Triangle, and core design choices (cadence, length, ownership, agenda).
  - Name the costs of sporadic or frequently-moved 1on1s.
  - Co-create a simple 1on1 checklist: Preparation, Execution, Aftermath.
  - Highlight active listening behaviors in 1on1s and preview the feedback model for the next lesson.
- In-session practice:
  - Design one concrete 1on1 experiment and a simple checklist they will test with a direct over the next two weeks.

### 4) 1:1s (depth) + Intro to Feedback (Manager Tools model)

- Brief review: Reflections on 1:1s.
- Core content:
  - 1:1 depth skills: asking vs telling, surfacing risks, coaching moments in the flow.
  - Transition to feedback as a daily tool, not an event.
  - Manager Tools feedback model:
    - Positive: “When you do X, here’s what happens. Thanks—keep it up.”
    - Adjusting: “When you do X, here’s what happens. Can you do Y instead?”
  - Why feedback works: fast, specific, behavior-focused, low drama.
- In-session practice:
  - Write 2 positive + 2 adjusting feedback statements from real situations.

### 5) Feedback + Nonviolent Communication (Rosenberg)

- Brief review: Reflections on feedback.
- Core content:
  - Contrast approaches:
    - MT feedback: short, frequent behavior-impact-request.
    - NVC: structured path for high emotion / high stakes conversations.
  - NVC components:
    - Observation (no evaluation), Feeling, Need, Request (specific, doable).
  - Translate between models:
    - MT feedback aligns with Observation/Impact/Request; NVC deepens “Need” and empathy.
  - Guardrails: avoid moral judgments, labels, “always/never,” mind-reading.
- In-session practice:
  - Convert one emotionally-charged situation into NVC language; role-play.

### 6) Radical Candor (Care Personally + Challenge Directly)

- Brief review: NVC attempts—where empathy helped and where it didn’t.
- Core content:
  - Radical Candor framework:
    - Care Personally: relationship, context, respect.
    - Challenge Directly: clarity, truth, standards.
  - Quadrants:
    - Radical Candor vs Ruinous Empathy vs Obnoxious Aggression vs Manipulative Insincerity.
  - How RC complements MT/NVC:
    - MT gives the micro-script; RC sets the cultural stance; NVC supports de-escalation.
  - Building a feedback culture: asking for feedback, rewarding truth-telling, normalizing revision.
- In-session practice:
  - Diagnose a real example into a quadrant; rewrite it as Radical Candor.

### 7) Case Studies I — Positive Feedback + Reinforcement (MT + RC)

- Brief review: Reflections on asking for feedback.
- Core content:
  - Case focus: reinforcing what “good” looks like without overpraising or being vague.
  - Precision: behavior, context, impact, and alignment to team standards.
  - Avoiding traps: personality praise, backhanded compliments, sarcasm.
- In-session practice:
  - Rapid-fire drills: rewrite vague praise into crisp MT positives; role-play delivery.

### 8) Case Studies II — Adjusting Feedback (low emotion, high frequency)

- Brief review: Reflections on positive feedback.
- Core content:
  - Case focus: correcting small misses early (punctuality, responsiveness, quality bar).
  - Managing defensiveness: calm tone, short script, stop after the ask.
  - Escalation ladder: repeat feedback, document patterns, align on standards.
- In-session practice:
  - Role-play: recipient gets defensive; manager stays on model.

### 9) Case Studies III — NVC for Conflict, Misinterpretation, and Tension

- Brief review: Reflections on adjusting feedback.
- Core content:
  - Case focus: conflict between peers, perceived disrespect, “tone” disputes.
  - NVC skills:
    - Separating observation from story, naming feelings/needs, making clean requests.
    - Empathic listening: reflect feelings/needs without agreeing with conclusions.
  - Rebuilding safety after conflict: repair attempts, expectations, and boundaries.
- In-session practice:
  - Triad exercise: speaker, listener (NVC), observer; rotate roles.

### 10) Case Studies IV — Combining MT + NVC + RC in High-Stakes Conversations

- Brief review: Reflections on conflict de-escalation.
- Core content:
  - Case focus: performance concerns, repeated behavior, trust damage.
  - Decision framework:
    - Use MT feedback for “simple behavior change.”
    - Use NVC when emotion, identity threat, or misunderstanding is high.
    - Use Radical Candor stance to stay kind and clear throughout.
  - Ending with commitments: who does what by when; how to follow up.
- In-session practice:
  - Full scenario role-play with a “conversation plan” and debrief.

### 11) Coaching I — Mentoring vs Coaching + The Coaching Habit (MBS)

- Brief review: Reflections on high-stakes conversations.
- Core content:
  - Mentoring vs coaching:
    - Mentoring: “I’ve been there; here’s advice.”
    - Coaching: “I’ll help you think; you own the solution.”
  - Coaching mindset: curiosity, restraint, empowerment.
  - The Coaching Habit basics:
    - “What’s on your mind?” (open)
    - “And what else?” (deeper)
    - “What’s the real challenge for you?” (focus)
- In-session practice:
  - Coach in pairs using 3 questions; manager practices not solving.

### 12) Coaching II — Habit-building, the “Lazy Question,” and Forward Accountability

- Brief review: Reflections on coaching.
- Core content:
  - Additional Coaching Habit questions:
    - “How can I help?” (clarify support without rescuing)
    - “If you’re saying yes to this, what are you saying no to?” (tradeoffs)
    - “What was most useful for you?” (close loop)
  - Coaching in 1:1s: when to coach vs when to direct.
  - Accountability without micromanaging: commitments, check-ins, learning review.
- In-session practice:
  - Practice “help without taking over” using real work dilemmas.

### 13) Delegation — Box and the Marbles, Bring Me a Rock, Eisenhower Matrix

- Brief review: Reflections on coaching and ownership.
- Core content:
  - Why delegation fails: unclear outcomes, unclear authority, unclear constraints.
  - “Bring Me a Rock” lesson: specify what “good” looks like (quality bar, examples, criteria).
  - “Box and the Marbles” concept: define:
    - The box (mission/outcome), the marbles (resources/constraints), and what can be changed.
  - Eisenhower Matrix:
    - Urgent/Important sorting; protect important-not-urgent work.
  - Delegation levels: do exactly, research & recommend, decide & inform, full ownership.
- In-session practice:
  - Pick one task to delegate; write the outcome, success criteria, constraints, and check-in plan.

