## Phase 2 — Team Leadership

### 14) Five Dysfunctions I (Lencioni) — Trust + Conflict

- Brief review: Reflections on delegation.
- Core content:
  - Overview of the model and why teams get stuck.
  - Dysfunction 1: Absence of Trust (vulnerability-based trust).
    - Indicators: guardedness, politics, fear of asking for help.
    - Interventions: leader vulnerability, personal histories, reliability loops.
  - Dysfunction 2: Fear of Conflict (artificial harmony).
    - Healthy conflict vs personal attacks; norms for debate.
- In-session practice:
  - Create team norms for conflict (“how we disagree”) and trust-building actions.

### 15) Five Dysfunctions II — Commitment + Accountability + Results

- Brief review: Reflections on inviting dissent.
- Core content:
  - Dysfunction 3: Lack of Commitment
    - Clarity beats consensus; “disagree and commit.”
  - Dysfunction 4: Avoidance of Accountability
    - Peer accountability; standards; calling “misses” early.
  - Dysfunction 5: Inattention to Results
    - Team outcomes over individual status; visible scoreboards.
  - Practical cadence: goals, meeting hygiene, and decision records.
- In-session practice:
  - Build a simple “commitment + accountability” template for decisions and follow-ups.

### 16) Agile & Scrum I — Principles, Roles, and Events

- Brief review: Reflections on accountability and commitment.
- Core content:
  - Agile mindset: iterative learning, customer value, transparency, adaptation.
  - Scrum roles: Product Owner, Scrum Master, Developers (and common anti-patterns).
  - Events: Sprint Planning, Daily Scrum, Review, Retrospective.
  - Definition of Done vs Definition of Ready; quality built-in.
- In-session practice:
  - Map your team’s current process onto Scrum events; identify gaps.

### 17) Agile & Scrum II — Backlogs, Estimation, Flow, and Predictability

- Brief review: Reflections on ceremony improvements.
- Core content:
  - Backlog refinement: slicing work, acceptance criteria, risk identification.
  - Estimation concepts (lightweight, not dogmatic): relative sizing; uncertainty.
  - Flow basics: WIP limits, blockers, cycle time vs velocity (why it matters).
  - Managing interrupts without destroying the sprint goal.
- In-session practice:
  - Take one large item and slice it into smaller, testable increments.

### 18) Agile & Scrum III — Leading Agile Teams (culture, autonomy, alignment)

- Brief review: Reflections on slicing and refinement.
- Core content:
  - Leadership behaviors that enable agility: clarity, empowerment, rapid learning.
  - Team autonomy with guardrails: outcomes, constraints, and decision rights.
  - Psychological safety in retros; blameless learning; action-oriented improvements.
  - Stakeholder management: transparency without thrash.
- In-session practice:
  - Design a retro format that produces real action items and follow-through.

### 19) The Advantage I (Lencioni) — Organizational Health + The 6 Questions

- Brief review: Reflections on agile leadership.
- Core content:
  - The premise: health as a competitive advantage (clarity + cohesion).
  - The 6 critical questions (team clarity):
    - Why do we exist?
    - How do we behave?
    - What do we do?
    - How will we succeed?
    - What is most important right now?
    - Who must do what?
  - Turning answers into language your team can repeat.
- In-session practice:
  - Draft “Why” and “How we behave” for your team in plain language.

### 20) The Advantage II — The Playbook (clarity into systems)

- Brief review: Share refined “Why/Behaviors” drafts; what got sharper?
- Core content:
  - Converting clarity into repeatable operating mechanisms:
    - Hiring/onboarding signals, meeting rhythms, decision-making norms.
  - Communication cascade: how leaders repeat messages until they stick.
  - Aligning projects to “what’s most important right now” to reduce thrash.
- In-session practice:
  - Build a lightweight “team playbook” outline (1–2 pages) and assign owners.

### 21) The Advantage III — The 4 Disciplines of Organizational Health + course wrap

- Brief review: Reflections on playbook implementation.
- Core content:
  - The 4 disciplines:
    - Build a cohesive leadership team.
    - Create clarity.
    - Over-communicate clarity.
    - Reinforce clarity through human systems.
  - Measurement and sustainability: leading indicators (behaviors) + lagging indicators (outcomes).
  - Personal leadership plan:
    - Your top 2 habits (from Trinity), your team norms, and your next 30 days.
- In-session practice:
  - Create a 30-day action plan with 2 behaviors, 2 rituals, and 1 metric.
  
